WEBVTT

00:24.400 --> 00:27.880
17. Spring.

00:29.040 --> 00:35.200
The opening of large tracts by the ice-cutters commonly causes a pond to break up earlier,

00:35.860 --> 00:42.440
for the water agitated by the wind, even in cold weather, wears away the surrounding ice.

00:43.760 --> 00:50.800
But such was not the effect on Walden that year, for she had soon got a thick new garment to take

00:50.800 --> 00:56.620
the place of the old. This pond never breaks up so soon as the others in this neighborhood.

00:57.460 --> 01:03.300
On account both of its greater depth, and its having no stream passing through it to melt or

01:03.300 --> 01:12.300
wear away the ice, I never knew it to open in the course of a winter, not accepting that of 5253,

01:12.340 --> 01:20.120
which gave the pond so severe a trial. It commonly opens about the 1st of April,

01:20.120 --> 01:27.360
a week or ten days later than Flint's Pond and Fairhaven, beginning to melt on the north side

01:27.360 --> 01:34.940
and in the shallower parts where it began to freeze. It indicates better than any water hereabouts

01:34.940 --> 01:41.420
the absolute progress of the season, being least affected by transient changes of temperature.

01:42.840 --> 01:49.800
A severe cold of a few days' duration in March may very much retard the opening of the former

01:49.800 --> 01:58.740
ponds, while the temperature of Walden increases almost uninterruptedly. A thermometer thrust into

01:58.740 --> 02:08.260
the middle of Walden on the 6th of March, 1847, stood at 32 degrees or freezing point, near the shore

02:08.260 --> 02:19.520
at 33 degrees, in the middle of Flint's Pond, the same day, at 32 plus degrees, at a dozen rods

02:19.520 --> 02:28.940
from the shore, in shallow water under ice a foot thick, at 36 degrees. This difference of three and a half

02:28.940 --> 02:35.640
degrees between the temperature of the deep water and the shallow in the latter pond, and the fact that a great

02:35.640 --> 02:41.940
proportion of it is comparatively shallow, show why it should break up so much sooner than Walden.

02:42.900 --> 02:52.620
The ice in the shallowest part was at this time several inches thinner than in the middle. In midwinter the middle

02:52.620 --> 03:01.640
had been the warmest and the ice thinnest there, so also every one who has waded about the shores of the pond

03:01.640 --> 03:08.220
in summer must have perceived how much warmer the water is close to the shore, where only three or four

03:08.220 --> 03:14.920
inches deep, then a little distance out, and on the surface where it is deep, then near the bottom.

03:16.300 --> 03:22.500
In spring the sun not only exerts an influence through the increased temperature of the air and earth,

03:23.960 --> 03:29.920
but its heat passes through ice a foot or more thick, and is reflected from the bottom in shallow

03:29.920 --> 03:37.500
water, and so also warms the water and melts the underside of the ice at the same time that it is

03:37.500 --> 03:45.240
melting it more directly above, making it uneven, and causing the air bubbles which it contains to

03:45.240 --> 03:53.180
extend themselves upward and downward until it is comparatively honeycombed, and at last disappears

03:53.180 --> 04:03.640
suddenly in a single spring rain. Ice has its grain as well as wood, and when a cake begins to rot or

04:03.640 --> 04:11.760
comb, that is assume the appearance of honeycomb, whatever may be its position, the air cells are at

04:11.760 --> 04:20.600
right angles with what was the water surface. Where there is a rock or a log rising near to the surface

04:20.600 --> 04:29.120
the ice over it is much thinner and is frequently quite dissolved by this reflected heat, and I have

04:29.120 --> 04:35.720
been told that in the experiment at Cambridge to freeze water in a shallow wooden pond through the

04:35.720 --> 04:43.080
cold air circulating underneath, and so had access to both sides, the reflection of the sun from the

04:43.080 --> 04:50.780
bottom more than counterbalanced this advantage. When a warm rain in the middle of the winter melts

04:50.780 --> 04:58.780
off the snow ice from Walden, and leaves a hard dark or transparent ice on the middle, there will be

04:58.780 --> 05:08.400
a strip of rotten though thicker white ice, a rod or more wide, about the shores, created by this

05:08.400 --> 05:15.220
reflected heat. Also, as I have said, the bubbles themselves within the ice operate as burning

05:15.220 --> 05:25.040
glasses to melt the ice beneath. The phenomena of the year take place every day in a pond on a small

05:25.040 --> 05:31.740
scale. Every morning, generally speaking, the shallow water is being warmed more rapidly than

05:31.740 --> 05:38.780
the deep, though it may not be made so warm after all, and every evening it is being cooled more

05:38.780 --> 05:48.480
rapidly until the morning. The day is an epitome of the year, the night is the winter, the morning

05:48.480 --> 05:56.120
and evening are the spring and fall, and the noon is the summer. The cracking and booming of the

05:56.120 --> 06:04.500
ice indicate a change of temperature. One pleasant morning, after a cold night, February 24, 1850,

06:05.120 --> 06:12.100
having gone to Flint's Pond to spend the day, I noticed with surprise that when I struck the

06:12.100 --> 06:21.440
ice with the head of my axe it resounded like a gong for many rods around, or as if I had struck

06:21.440 --> 06:30.220
on a tight drum head. The pond began to boom about an hour after sunrise when it felt the

06:30.220 --> 06:37.860
influence of the sun's rays slanted upon it from over the hills. It stretched itself and yawned

06:37.860 --> 06:46.140
like a waking man with a gradually increasing tumult, which was kept up three or four hours.

06:47.060 --> 06:54.500
It took a short siesta at noon, and boomed once more toward night as the sun was withdrawing its

06:54.500 --> 07:03.220
influence. In the right stage of the weather a pond fires its evening gun with great regularity,

07:04.020 --> 07:09.920
but in the middle of the day, being full of cracks and the air also being less elastic,

07:10.280 --> 07:15.780
it had completely lost its resonance, and probably fishes and muskrats could

07:15.780 --> 07:23.300
not then have been stunned by a blow on it. The fishermen say that the thundering of the

07:23.300 --> 07:29.480
pond scares the fishes and prevents their biting. The pond does not thunder every evening,

07:29.480 --> 07:36.240
and I cannot tell surely when to expect its thundering, but though I may perceive no

07:36.240 --> 07:43.720
difference in the weather, it does. Who would have suspected so large and cold and thick-skinned

07:43.720 --> 07:50.520
a thing to be so sensitive? Yet it has its law, to which it thunders obedience when it should,

07:50.520 --> 08:00.360
as surely as the buds expand in the spring. The earth is all alive and covered with papillae.

08:01.980 --> 08:11.300
The largest pond is as sensitive to atmospheric changes as the globule of mercury in its tube.

08:13.300 --> 08:18.480
One attraction in coming to the woods to live was that I should have leisure and opportunity

08:18.480 --> 08:24.400
to see the spring come in. The ice in the pond at length begins to be honeycombed,

08:24.860 --> 08:32.820
and I can set my heel in it as I walk. Fogs and rains and warmer suns are gradually melting the

08:32.820 --> 08:41.060
snow. The days have grown sensibly longer, and I see how I shall get through the winter without

08:41.060 --> 08:49.540
adding to my woodpile, for large fires are no longer necessary. I am on the alert for the first

08:49.540 --> 08:59.220
signs of spring, to hear the chants note of some arriving bird, while the striped squirrels chirp,

09:00.500 --> 09:08.200
for his stores must be now nearly exhausted, or see the woodchuck venture out of his winter quarters.

09:09.420 --> 09:15.520
On the thirteenth of March, after I had heard the bluebird, song sparrow, and red wing,

09:16.240 --> 09:23.360
the ice was still nearly a foot thick. As the weather grew warmer, it was not sensibly worn

09:23.360 --> 09:30.220
away by the water, nor broken up and floated off as in rivers, but though it was completely

09:30.220 --> 09:37.080
melted for half a rod in width about the shore, the middle was merely honeycombed and saturated

09:37.080 --> 09:44.200
with water, so that you could put your foot through it when six inches thick. But by the next day

09:44.200 --> 09:51.000
evening, perhaps, after a warm rain followed by fog, it would have wholly disappeared,

09:51.740 --> 10:00.240
all gone off with the fog, spirited away. One year I went across the middle only five

10:00.240 --> 10:08.460
days, before it disappeared entirely. In 1845 Walden was first comparatively open on the first

10:08.460 --> 10:20.120
of April. In 46, the 25th of March. In 47, the 8th of April. In 51, the 28th of March.

10:20.800 --> 10:30.560
In 52, the 18th of April. In 53, the 23rd of March. In 54, about the 7th of April.

10:32.320 --> 10:38.460
Every incident connected with the breaking up of the rivers and ponds and the settling of the

10:38.460 --> 10:44.620
weather is particularly interesting to us who live in a climate of so great extremes.

10:45.620 --> 10:54.000
When the warmer days come, they who dwell near the river hear the ice crack at night with a startling

10:54.000 --> 11:04.160
whoop as loud as artillery, as if its icy fetters were rent from end to end, and within a few days

11:04.160 --> 11:12.420
see it rapidly going out. So the alligator comes out of the mud with quakings of the earth.

11:13.620 --> 11:19.940
One old man who has been a close observer of Nature, and seems as thoroughly wise in regard

11:19.940 --> 11:27.940
to all her operations as if she had been put upon the stocks when he was a boy, he had helped to lay

11:27.940 --> 11:35.820
her keel, who has come to his growth and can hardly acquire more of natural lore if he should live to

11:35.820 --> 11:41.980
the age of Methuselah, told me, and I was surprised to hear him express wonder at any of Nature's

11:41.980 --> 11:48.780
operations, for I thought that there were no secrets between them, that one spring day he took

11:48.780 --> 11:55.140
his gun and boat, and thought that he would have a little sport with the ducks. There was ice still

11:55.140 --> 12:00.820
on the meadows, but it was all gone out of the river, and he dropped down without obstruction from

12:00.820 --> 12:07.920
Sudbury, where he lived, to Fairhaven Pond, which he found unexpectedly covered for the most part

12:07.920 --> 12:15.700
with a firm field of ice. It was a warm day, and he was surprised to see so great a body of ice

12:15.700 --> 12:23.560
remaining. Not seeing any ducks, he hid his boat on the north or back side of an island, in the pond,

12:23.580 --> 12:30.280
and then concealed himself in the bushes on the south side to await them. The ice was melted for

12:30.280 --> 12:37.360
three or four rods from the shore, and there was a smooth and warm sheet of water, with a muddy bottom,

12:37.360 --> 12:44.560
such as the ducks love, within, and he thought it likely, that some would be along pretty soon.

12:45.500 --> 12:52.640
After he had lain still there about an hour, he heard a low and seemingly very distant sound,

12:53.340 --> 13:00.200
but singularly grand and impressive, unlike anything he had ever heard, gradually swelling

13:00.200 --> 13:09.680
and increasing as if it would have a universal and memorable ending, a sullen rush and roar,

13:10.180 --> 13:17.040
which seemed to him all at once like the sound of a vast body of fowl coming in to settle there,

13:17.620 --> 13:24.660
and seizing his gun he started up in haste and excited, but he found to his surprise

13:24.660 --> 13:30.620
that the whole body of the ice had started, while he lay there, and drifted into the shore,

13:31.120 --> 13:39.540
and the sound he had heard was made by its edge grating on the shore, at first gently nibbled and

13:39.540 --> 13:46.000
crumbled off, but at length heaving up and scattering its wrecks along the island to a

13:46.000 --> 13:54.640
considerable height before it came to a standstill. At length the sun's rays have attained the right

13:54.640 --> 14:02.840
angle, and warm winds blow up mist and rain and melt the snow banks, and the sun dispersing the

14:02.840 --> 14:12.380
mist smiles on a checkered landscape of russet and white smoking with incense, through which

14:12.380 --> 14:20.860
the traveller picks his way from islet to islet, cheered by the music of a thousand tinkling reels

14:20.860 --> 14:27.600
and rivulets whose veins are filled with the blood of winter which they are bearing off.

14:29.280 --> 14:36.800
Few phenomena gave me more delight to observe the forms which thawing sand and clay assume

14:36.800 --> 14:42.100
in flowing down the sides of a deep cut on the railroad through which I passed on my way to the

14:42.100 --> 14:49.300
village. A phenomenon not very common on so large a scale, though the number of freshly exposed

14:49.300 --> 14:54.540
banks of the right material must have been greatly multiplied since railroads were invented.

14:55.640 --> 15:02.520
The material was sand of every degree of fineness and of rich colours commonly mixed with a little

15:02.520 --> 15:10.600
clay. When the frost comes out in the spring, and even in a thawing day in the winter, the sand

15:10.600 --> 15:18.300
begins to flow down the slopes like lava, sometimes bursting out through the snow and overflowing it,

15:18.300 --> 15:26.660
where no sand was to be seen before. Innumerable little streams overlap and interlace one with

15:26.660 --> 15:35.380
another, exhibiting a sort of hybrid product which obeys halfway the law of currents and halfway that

15:35.380 --> 15:46.120
of vegetation. As it flows it takes the form of sappy leaves or vines, making heaps of pulpy sprays

15:46.120 --> 15:53.660
foot or more in depth, and resembling, as you look down on them, the laciniated, lobed, and

15:53.660 --> 16:03.930
imbrogated thalluses of some lichens, or you are reminded of coral, of leopards' paws or birds' feats,

16:04.800 --> 16:14.260
of brains or lungs or bowels, and excrements of all kinds. It is a truly grotesque vegetation

16:14.890 --> 16:21.700
whose form and colour we see imitated in bronze, a sort of architectural foliage more ancient

16:21.700 --> 16:27.240
and typical than acanthus, chicory, ivy, vine, or any vegetable leaves,

16:28.500 --> 16:34.880
destined perhaps under some circumstances to become a puzzle to future geologists.

16:35.780 --> 16:43.880
The whole cut impressed me as if it were a cave with its stalactites laid open to the light.

16:44.900 --> 16:50.620
The various shades of the sand are singularly rich and agreeable,

16:52.420 --> 17:01.020
embracing the different iron colours brown, grey, yellowish, and reddish. When the flowing mass

17:01.020 --> 17:07.400
reaches the drain at the foot of the bank it spreads out flatter into strands, the separate

17:07.400 --> 17:13.220
streams losing their semi-cylindrical form, and gradually becoming more flat and broad,

17:13.220 --> 17:19.280
running together as they are more moist till they form an almost flat sand,

17:20.080 --> 17:25.480
still variously beautifully shaded, but in which you can trace the original forms of vegetation,

17:26.420 --> 17:34.140
till at length in the water itself they are converted into banks, like those formed off the

17:34.140 --> 17:40.160
mouths of rivers, and the forms of vegetation are lost and the ripple marks on the bottom.

17:41.140 --> 17:47.380
The whole bank, which is from twenty to forty feet high, is sometimes overlaid with a mass of

17:47.380 --> 17:55.040
this kind of foliage, or sandy rupture, for a quarter of a mile on one or both sides,

17:55.800 --> 18:03.500
the produce of one spring day. What makes this sand foliage remarkable is its springing into

18:03.500 --> 18:10.780
existence thus suddenly. When I see on the one side the inert bank, for the sun acts on

18:10.780 --> 18:18.620
one side first, and on the other this luxuriant foliage and the creation of an hour, I am affected

18:18.620 --> 18:28.600
as if in a peculiar sense I stood in the laboratory of the artist who made the world and me, had come

18:28.600 --> 18:37.060
to where he was still at work, sporting on this bank and with excess of energy strewing his fresh

18:37.060 --> 18:45.840
designs about. I feel as if I were nearer to the vitals of the globe, for this sandy overflow is

18:45.840 --> 18:55.520
something such a foliaceous mass as the vitals of the animal body. You find thus in the very

18:55.520 --> 19:04.280
sand an anticipation of the vegetable leaf. No wonder that the earth expresses itself outwardly

19:04.280 --> 19:13.340
in leaves. It so labors the idea inwardly. The atoms have already learned this law and are

19:13.340 --> 19:22.600
pregnant by it. The overhanging leaf sees here its prototype. Internally, whether in the globe or

19:22.600 --> 19:30.620
in the animal body, it is a moist thick lobe, a word especially applicable to the liver and lungs

19:30.620 --> 19:41.660
and the leaves of fat. Geni, labor, lapsus, to flow or slip downward, elapsing. Gias, globus, lobe,

19:42.340 --> 19:54.680
also lap, flap, and other words. Externally a dry thin leaf, even as the F and V are a pressed and

19:54.680 --> 20:06.980
dried B, the radicals of lobe are lb, the soft mass of the B, single-lobed or B double-lobed,

20:07.480 --> 20:20.720
with the liquid L behind it pressing it forward. In globe, glb, the guttural g adds to the meaning

20:20.720 --> 20:29.360
the capacity of the throat. The feathers and wings of birds are still drier and thinner leaves.

20:30.220 --> 20:36.780
Thus also you pass from the lumpish grub in the earth to the airy and fluttering butterfly.

20:37.620 --> 20:45.120
The very globe continually transcends and translates itself, and becomes winged in its orbit.

20:46.300 --> 20:54.400
Even ice begins with delicate crystal leaves as if it had flowed into molds which the fronds of

20:54.400 --> 21:01.600
water plants have impressed on the watery mirror. The whole tree itself is but one leaf,

21:02.020 --> 21:08.600
and rivers are still vaster leaves whose pulp is intervening earth,

21:09.600 --> 21:15.640
and towns and cities are the ova of insects in their axils.

21:16.560 --> 21:24.020
When the sun withdraws and the sand ceases to flow, but in the morning the streams will start

21:24.020 --> 21:32.680
and branch and branch again into a myriad of others, you here see perchance how blood vessels

21:32.680 --> 21:40.700
are formed. If you look closely you observe that first there pushes forward from the thawing mass

21:40.700 --> 21:50.840
a stream of softened sand with a drop-like point, like the ball of the finger feeling its way slowly

21:50.840 --> 21:57.720
and blindly downward until it lasts with more heat and moisture as the sun gets higher,

21:58.320 --> 22:06.440
the most fluid portion, in its effort to obey the law to which the most inert also yields,

22:07.580 --> 22:15.120
separates from the latter and forms for itself a meandering channel or artery within that,

22:15.120 --> 22:22.960
in which is seen a little silvery stream glancing like lightning from one stage of

22:22.960 --> 22:31.460
pulpy leaves or branches to another, and ever and anon swallowed up in the sand.

22:32.540 --> 22:39.260
It is wonderful how rapidly yet perfectly the sand organizes itself as it flows,

22:40.010 --> 22:45.740
using the best material its mass affords to form the sharp edges of its channel.

22:47.260 --> 22:53.200
Such are the sources of rivers, in the siliceous manner which the water deposits

22:53.790 --> 23:00.640
is perhaps the bony system, and in the still finer soil and organic matter

23:01.000 --> 23:09.840
the fleshy fiber or cellular tissue. What is man but a mass of thawing clay?

23:11.360 --> 23:20.480
The ball of the human finger is but a drop congealed. The fingers and toes flow to their

23:20.480 --> 23:28.740
extent from the thawing mass of the body. Who knows what the human body would expand and flow

23:28.740 --> 23:39.380
out to under a more genial heaven? Is not the hand a spreading palm leaf with its lobes and veins?

23:40.620 --> 23:49.300
The ear may be regarded fancifully as a lichen, umbilicaria, on the side of the head,

23:49.820 --> 23:56.800
with its lobe or drop. The lip, labium from labor,

23:58.380 --> 24:06.360
laps or lapses from the sides of the cavernous mouth. The nose is a manifest congealed drop

24:06.360 --> 24:14.380
or stalactite. The chin is a still larger drop, the confluent dripping of the face.

24:15.320 --> 24:20.780
The cheeks are a slide from the brows into the valleys of the face,

24:22.320 --> 24:28.640
opposed and diffused by the cheekbones. Each rounded lobe of the vegetable leaf, too,

24:29.160 --> 24:38.860
is a thick and now loitering drop, larger or smaller. The lobes are the fingers of the leaf,

24:38.860 --> 24:44.620
and as many lobes as it has, in so many directions it tends to flow,

24:44.900 --> 24:51.020
and more heat or other genial influences would have caused it to flow yet farther.

24:52.520 --> 24:57.900
Thus it seemed that this one hillside illustrated the principle of all the operations of nature.

24:57.900 --> 25:03.080
The maker of this earth but patented a leaf.

25:04.400 --> 25:15.480
What Champolian will decipher this hieroglyphic for us, that we may turn over a new leaf at last?

25:16.740 --> 25:23.760
This phenomenon is more exhilarating to me than the luxuriance and fertility of vineyards.

25:24.800 --> 25:31.780
True, it is somewhat excrementitious in its character, and there is no end to the heaps

25:31.780 --> 25:38.660
of liver, lights, and bowels, as if the globe were turned wrong side outward.

25:39.980 --> 25:49.720
But this suggests at least that nature has some bowels, and there again is mother of humanity.

25:50.680 --> 26:00.960
This is the frost coming out of the ground. This is spring. It precedes the green and flowery spring,

26:01.600 --> 26:09.280
as mythology precedes regular poetry. I know of nothing more purgative of winter fumes and

26:09.280 --> 26:19.700
indigestions. Fresh curls spring from the baldest brow. There is nothing inorganic.

26:20.600 --> 26:27.360
These foliaceous heaps lie along the bank like the slag of a furnace,

26:28.440 --> 26:38.080
showing that nature is in full blast within. The earth is not a mere fragment of dead history,

26:38.700 --> 26:44.660
stratum upon stratum like the leaves of a book to be studied by geologists and antiquaries

26:44.660 --> 26:54.300
chiefly, but living poetry like the leaves of a tree which precede flowers and fruit,

26:55.340 --> 27:04.300
not a fossil earth but a living earth, compared with whose great central life all animal and

27:04.300 --> 27:13.680
vegetable life is merely parasitic. Its throes will heave our exuviae from their graves. You may

27:13.680 --> 27:21.540
melt your metals and cast them into the most beautiful molds you can. They will never excite

27:21.540 --> 27:32.440
me like the forms which this molten earth flows out into, and not only it, but the institutions

27:32.440 --> 27:41.760
upon it are plastic like clay in the hands of the potter. Air long, not only on these banks,

27:41.760 --> 27:49.120
but on every hill and plain and in every hollow, the frost comes out of the ground like a dormant

27:49.120 --> 27:57.780
quadruped from its burrow, and seeks the sea with music, or migrates to other climes in clouds.

27:59.300 --> 28:05.160
Thaw, with his gentle persuasion, is more powerful than Thor with his hammer.

28:05.940 --> 28:13.940
The one melts, the other but breaks in pieces. When the ground was partially bare of snow,

28:14.000 --> 28:20.900
and a few warm days had dried its surface somewhat, it was pleasant to compare the first

28:20.900 --> 28:28.180
tender signs of the infant year just peeping forth with the stately beauty of the withered vegetation

28:28.180 --> 28:39.020
which had withstood the winter. Life everlasting, golden rods, pinweeds, and graceful wild grasses,

28:39.820 --> 28:47.220
more obvious and interesting frequently than in summer even, as if their beauty was not ripe

28:47.220 --> 28:57.320
till then. Even cotton grass, cattails, moulins, John's wort, hard hack, meadow sweet, and other

28:57.320 --> 29:07.000
strong-stemmed plants, those unexhausted granaries which entertain the earliest birds, decent weeds,

29:07.000 --> 29:14.520
at least, which widowed nature wears. I am particularly attracted by the arching and

29:14.520 --> 29:22.560
sheaf-like top of the wool grass. It brings back the summer to our winter memories, and is among

29:22.560 --> 29:29.160
the forms which art loves to copy, and which in the vegetable kingdom have the same relation

29:29.160 --> 29:38.640
to types already in the mind of man that astronomy has. It is an antique style,

29:39.260 --> 29:48.060
older than Greek or Egyptian. Many of the phenomena of winter are suggestive of an

29:48.060 --> 29:58.020
expressible tenderness and fragile delicacy. We are accustomed to hear this king described

29:58.020 --> 30:09.620
as a rude and boisterous tyrant, but with the gentleness of a lover he adorns the tresses of

30:09.620 --> 30:15.640
summer. At the approach of spring the red squirrels got under my house, two at a time,

30:15.640 --> 30:21.040
directly under my feet as I sat reading or writing, and kept up the queerest

30:21.040 --> 30:26.200
chuckling and chirruping and vocal pirouetting and gurgling sounds that ever were heard,

30:27.100 --> 30:34.820
and when I stamped they only chirruped the louder, as if past all fear and respect in their mad pranks,

30:35.340 --> 30:37.980
defying humanity to stop them.

30:39.240 --> 30:46.060
No, you don't. Chickadee, chickadee. They were wholly deaf to my arguments,

30:46.900 --> 30:52.760
or failed to perceive their force, and fell into a strain of invective that was irresistible.

30:53.320 --> 31:00.720
The first sparrow of spring, the year beginning with younger hope than ever,

31:01.640 --> 31:08.680
The faint silvery warblings heard over the partially bare and moist fields from the blue bird,

31:09.520 --> 31:16.740
the song sparrow and the red wing, as if the last flakes of winter tinkled as they fell.

31:18.800 --> 31:25.560
What at such a time are histories, chronologies, traditions, and all written revelations?

31:26.520 --> 31:31.440
The brooks sing carols and glee's to the spring.

31:32.900 --> 31:42.460
The marsh hawk, sailing low over the meadow, is already seeking the first slimy life that awakes.

31:43.380 --> 31:53.820
The sinking sound of melting snow is heard in all dells, and the ice dissolves apace in the ponds.

31:54.240 --> 31:59.060
The grass flames up on the hillsides like a spring fire.

32:07.260 --> 32:16.760
As if the earth sent forth an inward heat to greet the returning sun, not yellow,

32:17.480 --> 32:23.060
but green is the color of its flame, the symbol of perpetual youth.

32:23.480 --> 32:33.020
The grass blade, like a long green ribbon, streams from the sod into the summer,

32:34.420 --> 32:43.040
checked indeed by the frost, but anon pushing on again, lifting its spear of last year's hay

32:43.040 --> 32:51.580
with the fresh life below. It grows as steadily as the rill oozes out of the ground.

32:51.580 --> 32:59.400
It is almost identical with that, for in the growing days of June, when the rills are dry,

32:59.920 --> 33:08.000
the grass blades are their channels, and from year to year the herds drink at this perennial green

33:08.000 --> 33:19.540
stream, and the mower draws from it betimes their winter supply. So our human life but dies down to

33:19.540 --> 33:26.500
its root, and still puts forth its green blade to eternity.

33:29.000 --> 33:37.240
Walden is melting apace. There is a canal two rods wide along the northerly and westerly sides,

33:37.860 --> 33:44.080
and wider still at the east end. A great field of ice has cracked off from the main body.

33:44.810 --> 33:49.060
I hear a song sparrow singing from the bushes on the shore.

33:59.200 --> 34:08.220
He too is helping to crack it. How handsome the great sweeping curves in the edge of the ice,

34:09.180 --> 34:16.260
answering somewhat to those of the shore, but more regular. It is unusually hard,

34:16.560 --> 34:23.540
owing to the recent severe but transient cold, and all watered or waved like a palace floor.

34:24.820 --> 34:32.240
But the wind slides eastward over its opaque surface in vain, till it reaches the living

34:32.240 --> 34:42.080
surface beyond. It is glorious to behold this ribbon of water sparkling in the sun,

34:42.920 --> 34:53.440
the bare face of the pond full of glee and youth, as if it spoke the joy of the fishes within it,

34:53.650 --> 35:03.140
and of the sands on its shore, a silvery sheen as from the scales of a leuciscus,

35:03.960 --> 35:14.100
as it were all one active fish. Such is the contrast between winter and spring.

35:15.520 --> 35:24.560
Walden was dead, and is alive again. But this spring is broke up more steadily,

35:24.620 --> 35:32.680
as I have said. The change from storm and winter to serene and mild weather, from dark and sluggish

35:32.680 --> 35:41.860
hours to bright and elastic ones, is a memorable crisis which all things proclaim. It is seemingly

35:41.860 --> 35:51.980
instantaneous at last. Suddenly an influx of light filled my house, though the evening was at hand,

35:52.460 --> 35:59.000
and the clouds of winter still overhung it, and the eaves were dripping with sleety rain.

35:59.880 --> 36:09.420
I looked out the window, and lo! where yesterday was cold gray ice there lay the transparent pond,

36:10.380 --> 36:19.480
already calm and full of hopes as in a summer evening, reflecting a summer evening sky in its

36:19.480 --> 36:28.760
bosom, though none was visible overhead, as if it had intelligence with some remote horizon.

36:29.900 --> 36:36.080
I heard a robin in the distance, the first I had heard for many a thousand years, me thought.

36:36.920 --> 36:47.840
The same sweet and powerful song as of yore. Oh, the evening robin at the end of a New England

36:47.840 --> 36:58.240
summer day! If I could ever find the twig he sits upon, I mean he, I mean the twig.

36:59.040 --> 37:09.500
This, at last, is not the Turdus migratorius. The pitch pines and shrub oaks about my house,

37:09.960 --> 37:16.060
which had so long drooped, suddenly resumed their several characters, looked brighter,

37:16.300 --> 37:23.680
greener, and more erect and alive, as if effectually cleansed and restored by the rain.

37:24.580 --> 37:31.720
I knew that it would not rain any more. You may tell by looking at any twig of the forest,

37:32.040 --> 37:36.160
ay, at your very wood-pile, whether its winter is past or not.

37:38.020 --> 37:44.860
As it grew darker, I was startled by the honking of geese, flying low over the woods like

37:45.840 --> 37:52.420
weary travelers getting in late from southern lakes, and indulging at last in unrestrained

37:52.420 --> 38:01.300
complaint and mutual consolation. Standing at my door, I could hear the rush of their wings.

38:02.120 --> 38:08.740
When, driving toward my house, they suddenly spied my light, and with hushed clamor wheeled

38:09.300 --> 38:19.800
and settled in the pond. So I came in, and shut the door, and passed my first spring night in the

38:19.800 --> 38:27.120
woods. In the morning I watched the geese from the door through the mist, sailing in the middle

38:27.120 --> 38:35.640
of the pond, fifty rods off, so large and tumultuous that Walden appeared like an artificial pond for

38:35.640 --> 38:43.280
their amusement. But when I stood on the shore they at once rose up with a great flapping of wings

38:43.280 --> 38:49.200
at the signal of their commander, and when they had got into rank circled about over my head,

38:49.200 --> 38:56.480
twenty-nine of them, and then steered straight to Canada, with a regular honk from the leader

38:56.480 --> 39:04.140
at intervals, trusting to break their fast in muddier pools. A plump of ducks rose at the same

39:04.140 --> 39:11.740
time and took the route to the north in the wake of their noisier cousins. For a week I heard the

39:11.740 --> 39:19.440
groping clanger of some solitary goose in the foggy mornings, seeking its companion,

39:20.060 --> 39:26.340
and still peopling the woods with the sound of a larger life than they could sustain.

39:27.960 --> 39:35.060
In April the pigeons were seen again flying express in small flocks, and in due time I

39:35.060 --> 39:40.920
heard the Martins twittering over my clearing, though it had not seemed that the township

39:40.920 --> 39:48.740
contained so many that it could afford me any, and I fancied that they were peculiarly of the

39:48.740 --> 39:57.340
ancient race that dwelt in hollow trees ere white men came. In almost all climes the tortoise and the

39:57.340 --> 40:06.440
frog are among the precursors and heralds of this season, and birds fly with song and glancing

40:06.440 --> 40:16.520
plumage, and plants spring and bloom and winds blow to correct this slight oscillation of the

40:16.520 --> 40:24.000
poles and preserve the equilibrium of nature. As every season seems best to us in its turn,

40:24.400 --> 40:31.840
so the coming of spring is like the creation of cosmos out of chaos and the realization

40:31.840 --> 40:34.260
of the golden age.

40:51.400 --> 41:00.420
The east wind withdrew to Aurora and the Nabataean kingdom, and the Persian and the ridges placed

41:00.420 --> 41:11.220
under the morning rays. Man was born, whether the artificer of things, the origin of a better world,

41:11.840 --> 41:19.600
made him from the divine seed, or the earth, being recent and lately sundered from the high ether,

41:20.520 --> 41:28.700
retained some seeds of cognate heaven. A single gentle rain makes the grass many

41:28.700 --> 41:35.900
shades greener, so our prospects brighten on the influx of better thoughts. We should be blessed

41:35.900 --> 41:41.980
if we lived in the present always, and took advantage of every accident that befell us,

41:42.640 --> 41:49.680
like the grass which confesses the influence of the slightest dew that falls on it, and did not

41:49.680 --> 41:57.440
spend our time in atoning for the neglect of past opportunities, which we call doing our duty.

41:58.700 --> 42:10.100
We loiter in winter while it is already spring. In a pleasant spring morning all men's sins are forgiven.

42:12.020 --> 42:22.900
Such a day is a truce to vice. While such a sun holds out to burn, the vilest sinner may return.

42:24.040 --> 42:30.960
Through our own recovered innocence we discern the innocence of our neighbors.

42:32.780 --> 42:38.420
You may have known your neighbor yesterday for a thief, a drunkard, or a sensualist,

42:38.880 --> 42:46.300
and merely pitied or despised him, and despaired of the world. But the sun

42:46.300 --> 42:57.800
shines bright and warm this first spring morning, recreating the world, and you meet him at some

42:58.140 --> 43:09.660
serene work, and see how it is exhausted and debauched veins expand with still joy,

43:09.660 --> 43:19.520
and bless the new day, feel the spring influence with the innocence of infancy,

43:20.480 --> 43:30.160
and all his faults are forgotten. There is not only an atmosphere of goodwill about him,

43:30.160 --> 43:42.280
but even a savor of holiness groping for expression, blindly and ineffectually perhaps,

43:42.920 --> 43:53.020
like a newborn instinct. And for a short hour the south hillside echoes to no vulgar jest.

43:53.020 --> 44:03.260
And you see some innocent fair shoots preparing to burst from his gnarled rind and try another

44:03.260 --> 44:16.220
year's life, tender and fresh as the youngest plant. Even he has entered into the joy of his lord.

44:17.800 --> 44:24.600
Why the jailer does not leave open his prison doors, why the judge does not dismiss his case,

44:24.640 --> 44:32.040
why the preacher does not dismiss his congregation, it is because they do not obey the hint

44:32.620 --> 44:38.930
which God gives them, nor accept the pardon which he freely offers to all.

44:41.110 --> 44:49.190
A return to goodness produced each day, in the tranquil and beneficent breath of the morning,

44:50.290 --> 44:58.230
causes that in respect to the love of virtue and the hatred of vice, one approaches a little

44:58.230 --> 45:05.240
the primitive nature of man, as the sprouts of the forest which has been felled.

45:05.940 --> 45:15.060
In like manner, the evil which one does in the interval of a day prevents the germs of virtues

45:15.060 --> 45:22.340
which began to spring up again from developing themselves and destroys them.

45:23.380 --> 45:29.740
After the germs of virtue have thus been prevented many times from developing themselves,

45:29.740 --> 45:36.180
then the beneficent breath of evening does not suffice to preserve them.

45:36.880 --> 45:41.220
As soon as the breath of evening does not suffice longer to preserve them,

45:41.980 --> 45:48.600
then the nature of man does not differ much from that of the brute. Men,

45:48.620 --> 45:55.780
seeing the nature of this man like that of a brute, think that he has never possessed the

45:55.780 --> 46:03.620
faculty of reason. Are those the true and natural sentiments of man?

46:04.660 --> 46:12.540
The Golden Age was first created, which without any avenger, spontaneously without law,

46:13.240 --> 46:19.600
cherished fidelity and rectitude. Punishment and fear were not,

46:19.600 --> 46:27.200
nor were threatening words read on suspended brass, nor did the suppliant crowd fear the

46:27.200 --> 46:36.880
words of their judge, but were safe without an avenger. Not yet the pine felled on its mountains,

46:37.380 --> 46:45.240
had descended to the liquid waves that it might see a foreign world, and mortals knew no shores

46:45.240 --> 46:55.560
but their own. There was eternal spring, and placid zephyrs with warm blasts

46:56.280 --> 47:00.600
soothed the flowers, born without seed.

47:01.740 --> 47:07.700
On the 29th of April, as I was fishing from the bank of the river near the nine-acre corner bridge,

47:08.220 --> 47:13.040
standing on the quaking grass and willow roots, where the muskrats lurk,

47:13.680 --> 47:19.720
I heard a singular rattling sound, somewhat like that of the sticks which boys play with

47:19.720 --> 47:27.280
their fingers. When looking up I observed a very slight and graceful hawk, like a night-hawk,

47:28.180 --> 47:33.480
alternately soaring like a ripple, and tumbling a rod or two over and over,

47:34.060 --> 47:38.920
showing the underside of its wings which gleamed like a satin ribbon in the sun,

47:38.920 --> 47:46.780
or like the pearly inside of a shell. This sight reminded me of falconry,

47:47.560 --> 47:55.560
and what nobleness and poetry are associated with that sport. The Merlin, it seemed, to me,

47:55.740 --> 48:05.000
it might be called, but I care not for its name. It was the most ethereal flight I had ever witnessed.

48:05.740 --> 48:11.960
It did not simply flutter like a butterfly, nor soar like the larger hawks,

48:12.560 --> 48:18.100
but it sported with proud reliance in the fields of air.

48:19.040 --> 48:27.260
Mounting again and again with its strange chuckle, it repeated its free and beautiful fall,

48:28.240 --> 48:33.720
turning over and over like a kite, and then recovering from its lofty tumbling,

48:33.720 --> 48:42.480
as if it had never set its foot on terra firma. It appeared to have no companion in the universe,

48:43.540 --> 48:52.840
sporting there alone, and to need none, but the mourning and the ether with which it played,

48:53.920 --> 48:59.620
it was not lonely, but made all the earth lonely beneath it.

49:00.500 --> 49:07.480
Where was the parent which hatched it, its kindred and its father in the heavens?

49:08.980 --> 49:16.220
The tenant of the air, it seemed related to the earth but by an egg hatched some time

49:16.220 --> 49:23.580
in the crevice of a crag, or was its native nest made in the angle of a cloud,

49:24.140 --> 49:30.500
woven of the rainbows, trimmings, and the sunset sky, and lined with some soft

49:30.500 --> 49:38.040
midsummer haze caught up from earth, its airy, now some cliffy cloud.

49:39.240 --> 49:43.640
Beside this I got a rare mess of golden and silver and bright

49:43.640 --> 49:47.820
cupreous fishes, which looked like a string of jewels.

49:49.380 --> 49:55.780
Ah, I have penetrated to those meadows on the morning of many a first spring day,

49:56.380 --> 50:02.100
jumping from hummock to hummock, from willow root to willow root, when the wild river valley

50:02.100 --> 50:08.660
and the woods were bathed in so pure and bright a light as would have waked the dead

50:08.660 --> 50:13.260
if they had been slumbering in their graves, as some suppose.

50:13.260 --> 50:18.420
There needs no stronger proof of immortality.

50:19.660 --> 50:23.200
All things must live in such a light.

50:24.580 --> 50:30.660
O death, where was thy sting? O grave, where was thy victory then?

50:31.840 --> 50:38.720
Our village life would stagnate if it were not for the unexplored forests and meadows

50:38.720 --> 50:47.320
which surround it. We need the tonic of wildness, to wade sometimes in marshes where the bittern

50:47.320 --> 50:54.760
and the meadow hen lurk, and hear the booming of the snipe, to smell the whispering sedge

50:54.760 --> 51:02.190
where only some wilder and more solitary fowl builds her nest, and the mink crawls with its

51:02.190 --> 51:09.930
close to the ground. At the same time that we are earnest to explore and learn all things,

51:10.650 --> 51:21.150
we require that all things be mysterious and unexplorable, that land and sea be infinitely

51:21.150 --> 51:28.530
wild, unsurveyed and unfathomed by us because unfathomable.

51:29.550 --> 51:40.230
We can never have enough of nature. We must be refreshed by the sight of inexhaustible vigor,

51:41.190 --> 51:48.710
vast and titanic features, the sea-coast with its wrecks, the wilderness with its living

51:48.710 --> 51:56.290
and its decaying trees, the thunder-cloud, and the rain which lasts three weeks and produces

51:56.290 --> 52:07.550
freshets. We need to witness our own limits transgressed, and some life pasturing freely

52:07.550 --> 52:15.110
where we never wander. We are cheered when we observe the vulture feeding on the carrion which

52:15.110 --> 52:21.910
disgusts and disheartens us, and deriving health and strength from the repast.

52:22.550 --> 52:28.970
There was a dead horse in the hollow by the path to my house, which compelled me sometimes to go

52:28.970 --> 52:35.110
out of my way, especially in the night when the air was heavy, but the assurance it gave me

52:35.730 --> 52:43.010
of the strong appetite and inviolable health of nature was my compensation for this.

52:43.910 --> 52:53.270
I love to see that nature is so rife with life, that myriads can be afforded to be sacrificed

52:53.270 --> 53:03.690
and suffered to prey on one another, that tender organizations can be so serenely squashed out of

53:03.690 --> 53:12.990
existence like pulp, tadpoles which herons gobble up, and tortoises and toads run over in the road

53:12.990 --> 53:23.570
and that sometimes it has rained flesh and blood. With a liability to accident we must see

53:23.770 --> 53:31.190
how little account is to be made of it. The impression made on a wise man is that of

53:31.190 --> 53:41.410
universal innocence. Poison is not poisonous after all, nor are any wounds fatal.

53:42.570 --> 53:53.110
Compassion is a very untenable ground. It must be expeditious. Its pleadings will not bear to be

53:53.110 --> 54:01.570
stereotyped. Early in May the oaks, hickories, maples, and other trees, just putting out amidst

54:01.570 --> 54:07.630
the pine woods around the pond, imparted a brightness like sunshine to the landscape,

54:08.730 --> 54:15.730
especially in cloudy days, as if the sun were breaking through mists and shining faintly on

54:15.730 --> 54:21.850
the hillsides as here and there. On the third or fourth of May I saw a loon in the pond,

54:22.650 --> 54:29.090
and during the first week of the month I heard the whippoorwill, the brown thrasher, the veerie,

54:29.090 --> 54:38.930
the wood peewee, the chawink, and other birds. I had heard the wood thrush long before. The Phoebe

54:38.930 --> 54:44.790
had already come once more and looked in at my door and window to see if my house was cavern-like

54:44.790 --> 54:53.190
enough for her, sustaining herself on humming wings with clinched talons, as if she held by the air,

54:53.190 --> 55:00.930
which she surveyed the premises. The sulphur-like pollen of the pitch pine soon covered the ground,

55:01.570 --> 55:07.370
and the stones and rotten wood along the shore, so that you could have collected a barrelful.

55:08.390 --> 55:19.010
This is the sulphur showers we bear of. Even in Calidas's drama of Sacontala we read of

55:19.010 --> 55:20.490
the

55:20.490 --> 55:34.270
And so the seasons went rolling on into summer, as one rambles into higher and higher grass.

55:36.750 --> 55:43.980
Thus was my first year's life in the woods completed, and the second year was similar to it.

55:43.980 --> 55:51.280
I finally left Walden, September 6, 1847.

